	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Sunmoon</b><br /><i>If the above is true, that is utter crap. Wizards would never be able to use big nukes, rogues could never BS, etc. Clerics would be blowing mana all over the place frantically trying to keep the next person alive.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>While I agree, this seems in line with the little bits and pieces of hard data I've seen elsewhere.<br />
<br />
The best place to check for similar problems is the wizard boards, since their nukes are most in line with our archery. (i.e. highly impulsive damage - I'm not saying Ranger DPS == Wizard DPS, thanks. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /> )<br />
<br />
A wizard over on Graffe's posted a quick experiment regarding one of the loroks in PoS.  It seems he took aggro doing about 1/5th the total damage that a bard had done, with what seemed reasonably spaced nukes.  (i.e. At the time he was aggro'd, he'd done 1/5th damage.  Not he did all the damage, then it took until it was roughly 1/5th until he was deaggrod.)<br />
<br />
This would also tend to explain why some folks don't seem to have problems.  As long as someone else is around to do more impulse damage, or you don't crit heavily or the like, you'll not really notice any difference.<br />
<br />
If this is how they're calculating aggro, it's incredibly silly, though.  It'd basically throw out 4 or so years of learning how the game works and how to play your class all around, not just for rangers and wizards.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
