<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Beohram</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jul 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Let&#8217;s think about what it was that Verant was trying to fix, and how they might have gone about fixing it.<br />
<br />
Verant says that they wanted to make sure that people who attacked from Range were properly added to the Hate list.<br />
<br />
<b>Question:</b>  Why were they not added to the Hate list before?  What is different about attacking from Range vs attacking up close?<br />
<br />
<b>Random thought.</b>  Everyone who has used a bow knows that you get two messages from every hit you land with your bow.<br />
<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:24 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 364 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:24 2003] You hit A Valorian Guardian for 364 points of damage.<br />
<br />
<br />
However, have you ever noticed that you can get too far from a mob to see the damage part of the hit?  And when this happens all you see is the Non-melee message?<br />
<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:45 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 192 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:47 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 180 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:57 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 552 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:56:59 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 356 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:57:04 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 184 points of damage.<br />
[Sun Mar 09 21:57:05 2003] A Valorian Guardian was hit by non-melee for 84 points of damage.<br />
<br />
<br />
What if it was this fact that was causing anyone over a 150 feet from a mob to be kept off the hate list?  Basically, just as you can get too far from a mob to see the &#8220;You hit A&#8221; portion of a hit, so to would the mob fail to see it.  (how far from a mob do you need to be to not see that line?)  What if in some way the mob were seeing damage done to itself in a similar way that we see the damage we do it?  It would never know it was being attacked.  (assuming a Mob was never told to look for the Non-melee part of the text script)<br />
<br />
How could this be fixed?  Simple, tell the mob to look for the Non-melee line of the Text.  The one line it may have been missing.  Now if we stayed outside the Range of attack where a Mob was ONLY seeing this line of text it would be a good fix.  But what if you never told the mob to now ignore the "You hit A&#8221; line?  Now every time a Ranger attacked from INSIDE this range (i.e. at any distance where the mob would normally see both lines of text) the newly programmed mob would be reading, and taking into account, twice the amount of damage really being done to it.<br />
<br />
Just a random though.</p>
	
	
	
