<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Maian62</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	Location: Sydney
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>A few observations.<br />
<br />
If "spike" damage is attracting more Hate - could this mean that big heavy 2-handers will pull more aggro than dual-wield now, making dual-wield a better way to go for non-tanks???<br />
<br />
I agree with the posters - that this might in effect be an AI change on the mobs - and not an illogical one at that.  It makes perfect sense for the mob to try to finish off the wizzy, if the wizzy has just nuked you for 2k or so.<br />
<br />
However, if so, it does of course overturn all the established aggro control strategies. Seems unlikely to me that SOE would intentionally set out to rewrite the book on aggro control.  So I'm tipping its either a bug, or a feature in need of radical retuning.  But - what if it was working as intended?<br />
<br />
Would you see a setup like this?<br />
Main tank has a big heavy weapon - with a nice big proc effect and plenty of dex.<br />
Assists have fast, light weapons, no big procs and no big hits.<br />
Groups and raids prefer casters to dot instead of nuke, but dots and debuffs can go on pretty much straight away.  Those who can only nuke, have to use lighter nukes in the early stages, saving the big nukes up purely for finishing off.<br />
<br />
Ranger archery would be considered "nuking" under these circumstances.  It would very likely cause archery to be shelved on raids - except perhaps as a way of pulling aggro off a caster...<br />
<br />
A lot of encounters would become noticably harder - though in the longer term - would that be an entirely undersirable thing?</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=216170">Magelo Profile</a></div>
	
	
