	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Rumuchii</b><br /><i>I know that I am too low to have the problems you guys are facing, but I see what you are saying.  But it really makes sense to me.  When you attack a mob, and get an add.  Who do you kill first?  Depends on the mob right?  Now say there is a gnoll in HHP that you pull.  He is regular old melee monster.  Now your add is a shaman, he stays a little ways back, and starts casting on you.  Who do you go after?  The shaman, he has less hp's but does more dmg, and helps his friend do more dmg with his spells (debuffs and such).  Seems to me it is a little AI at play here.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>This makes sense in a real combat situation, however, the way EQ has been designed, this type of system just isn't workable.  When you consider higher level mobs have been tuned to do damage to make a fight challenging with a plate class tanking, to suddenly change aggro rules in that fashion is game-breaking.  When you have a mob that can kill a PC caster or chain melee in the blink of an eye, you can't change aggro rules without compensating for the fact that much weaker classes will be taking aggro.  That type of change effectively cripples casters and chain melee classes.</p>
	
	
	
