	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I duo with a paladin regularly and she's very good about keeping aggro(unless I want it of course). We had both been watching the discussions of the changes(discussion? lol sorry.. the hair pulling ranting). We started doing a little testing.<br />
<br />
All setups for me were dual wielding an ornate sword of the general and swifty with call of fire up and eyepatch haste.<br />
<br />
Normally with her chain stunning she's never lost aggro unless I have to drop multiple snares and am nuking heavily.<br />
<br />
We tried with her normal setup of primal brawl stick.<br />
Pong<br />
<br />
Next was Edge of Honor<br />
Pong<br />
<br />
Last was her using epic.<br />
Better but still had a bit of pong.<br />
<br />
I most often got aggro right after a proc. Also once I got aggro it was very hard for her sometimes to get it back. Especially if it took more then a couple seconds.<br />
<br />
Next thing we did was do all the setups again but this time I gave her a damage shield.<br />
<br />
She held aggro almost everytime. If she lost it she regained it almost immediately and there was no pong.<br />
<br />
We tried a brief test with archery but because I'm not am3 or have a decent bow I don't think I can test it well enough.<br />
<br />
What does all this mean in my opinion? The nonmelee idea seems to be holding true. I'm not sure what the change is whether it's counting extra messages or what but nonmelee seems to be the part having an impact with the new aggro.<br />
I don't relish the idea of turning off all my damage shields to shed aggro quicker but that may be something to start on.</p>
	
	
	
