	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I'm truly getting disgusted, hung out in tatics with my regular group, but botting my ranger (63 am3/eq obs. comp bow)<br />
<br />
Paladin, shaman, chanter, rogue, ranger, cleric.  Pretty good group, been playing together for 5 months or so. <br />
<br />
Never, ever, have I been able to strip aggro off my Paladin, and that was trying hard.  He couldn't keep the things off the Ranger or me.  We let him tank it to 80%, second backstab crit I get chewed up. Any bow crit, bee line for the Ranger and god forbid if the bow proc'd. <br />
<br />
I really have to subscribe to the theory that the aggro list is inappropriatly raising players up to the top. Look at it like a roadblock effect that is happening where the crits are staying in the monsters memory, and it's impossible to drop below that point in the aggro list. So a crit for 2000 would have you permantly at 2000 aggro, jolt or no. Then you stack another crit for 1100 and you are at permant 3100 aggro. That might explain how Rangers Rogues and Wizzies are dropping immediatly after main tanks are- rather then the clerics who have been healing the tanks for thousands of points of damage?<br />
<br />
I know SOE was attempting to make it so everyone who did damage was going to be on the hate list. I think they just made the mobs remember certain types of damage better then others. Maybe look at how/if the crits are staying in the hate list , and see if thats one of the issues. <br />
<br />
Just one other theory- I think they might have tried seperate hate lists for each class, instead of one single list for everyone involved with a certain mob.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
